## 5 Extension: general multi-label losses

In this section, we broaden our analysis to cover a more extensive family of multi-label losses, including all common ones and a new extension defined based on linear-fractional functions with respect to the confusion matrix. Note that several loss functions are defined over the space \(\left\{0,1\right\}^{l}\), rather than \(\left\{+1,-1\right\}^{l}\). To accommodate this difference, any pair \(y,y^{\prime}\in\mathcal{Y}=\left\{+1,-1\right\}^{l}\) can be projected onto \(\left\{0,1\right\}^{l}\) by letting \(\overline{y}=\frac{y^{\prime}\pm 1}{2}\) and \(\overline{y^{\prime}}=\frac{y^{\prime}\pm 1}{2}\), where \(1\in\mathbb{R}^{l}\) is the vector with all elements equal to 1. Several common multi-label losses are defined as follows.

**Hamming loss:**\(\overline{\mathbb{L}}(y^{\prime},y)=\sum_{i=1}^{l}1_{y_{i},y_{i}y_{i}^{\prime}}\).

\(F_{\beta}\)**-measure loss:**\(\overline{\mathbb{L}}(y^{\prime},y)=1-\frac{\left(1+\beta^{2}\right) \overline{y^{\prime}}\cdot\overline{y}}{\beta^{2}\left\|\overline{y}\right\| _{1}+\left\|\overline{y^{\prime}}\right\|_{1}}\).

**Subset \(0/1\) loss:**\(\overline{\mathbb{L}}(y^{\prime},y)=\max_{i\in[l]}1_{y_{i}^{\prime}y_{i}}\).

**Jaccard distance:**\(\overline{\mathbb{L}}(y^{\prime},y)=1-\frac{\overline{y^{\prime}}\cdot\overline{y}}{ \left\|\overline{y}\right\|_{1}+\left\|\overline{y^{\prime}}\right\|_{1}- \overline{y^{\prime}}\cdot y}\)

**Precision@\(\kappa\):**: \(\overline{\mathsf{L}}(y^{\prime},y)=1-\frac{1}{\kappa}\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}(\overline {y}^{\prime})}1_{\overline{y}_{i}=1}\) subject to \(y^{\prime}\in\mathcal{Y}_{\kappa}\), where \(\mathcal{Y}_{\kappa}=\{y\in\mathcal{Y}\colon\left|\overline{y}\right|_{1}=\kappa\}\) and \(\mathcal{T}(\overline{y}^{\prime})=\{i\in[l]\colon\overline{y}_{i}^{\prime}=1\}\).
**Recall@\(\kappa\):**: \(\overline{\mathsf{L}}(y^{\prime},y)=1-\frac{1}{\left|\overline{y}\right|_{1}} \sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}(\overline{y})}1_{\overline{y}_{i}=1}\) subject to \(y^{\prime}\in\mathcal{Y}_{\kappa}\), where \(\mathcal{Y}_{\kappa}=\{y\in\mathcal{Y}\colon\left|\overline{y}\right|_{1}=\kappa\}\) and \(\mathcal{T}(\overline{y}^{\prime})=\{i\in[l]\colon\overline{y}_{i}^{\prime}=1\}\).

More generally, we can define a multi-label loss based on true positives (TP), true negatives (TN), false positives (FP) and false negatives (FN), which can be written explicitly as follows:

\[\mathsf{TP} =\overline{y}^{\prime}\cdot\overline{y}\quad\mathsf{TN}=\left| \overline{y}\right|_{1}-\overline{y}^{\prime}\cdot\overline{y}\] \[\mathsf{FP} =\left|\overline{y}^{\prime}\right|_{1}-\overline{y}^{\prime} \cdot\overline{y},\quad\mathsf{FN}=l+\overline{y}^{\prime}\cdot\overline{y}- \left|\overline{y}\right|_{1}-\left|\overline{y}^{\prime}\right|_{1}\]

Similar to (Koyejo et al., 2014, 2015), we now define a general family of multi-label losses as linear-fractional functions in terms of these four quantities:

\[\overline{\mathsf{L}}(y^{\prime},y)=\frac{a_{0}+a_{11}\mathsf{TP}+a_{10} \mathsf{FP}+a_{01}\mathsf{FN}+a_{00}\mathsf{TN}}{b_{0}+b_{11}\mathsf{TP}+b_{1 0}\mathsf{FP}+b_{01}\mathsf{FN}+b_{00}\mathsf{TN}}.\] (16)

It can be shown that the aforementioned Hamming loss, \(F_{\beta}\)-measure loss, Jaccard distance, precision and recall all belong to this family. Note that the previous definitions in (Koyejo et al., 2014, 2015) are within the empirical utility maximization (EUM) framework (Ye et al., 2012), where the measures are directly defined as functions of the population. We generalize their definition to the decision theoretic analysis (DTA) framework, in terms of loss functions defined over \(y\) and \(y^{\prime}\).

Moreover, we can consider extending multi-label losses (16) to non-linear fractional functions of these four quantities, or more generally, to any other forms, as long as they are defined over the space \(\mathcal{Y}\times\mathcal{Y}\).

Another important family of multi-label losses is the _tree distance_ loss, used in cases of hierarchical classes. In many practical applications, the class labels exist within a predefined hierarchy. For example, in the image tagging problem, class labels might include broad categories such as 'animals' or'vehicles', which further subdivide into more specific classes like'mammals' and 'birds' for animals, or 'cars' and 'trucks' for vehicles. Each of these subcategories can be divided even further, showcasing a clear hierarchical structure.

